    "This structure facilitates a dynamic learning process, where the actor adjusts its policy based on feedback from the critic [32].",
    "This feedback loop is crucial for improving the policy iteratively, allowing the actor to learn from its experiences and make better decisions over time.",
    "Moreover, actor-critic algorithms can handle large and continuous action spaces more effectively than purely value-based methods, making them suitable for complex real-world applications.",
    "The ability to perform online learning, where the policy is continuously updated as new data becomes available, further enhances their practicality in dynamic environments [33].An advancement in this area is the differentiation between standard gradient and natural gradient techniques for policy updates.",
    "Standard gradient methods update the policy parameters by moving in the direction that most steeply reduces the cost function, a process which can be inefficient in complex parameter spaces."
